               <item n="m_translation_old">a1 he who was Śilpavān is [now] to be known as Aniruddha. He who was Prajñavān, is now to be known as Śāriputra.
a2 He who at that time was Puṇyavān, I was he. Also at that time by the power of virtue I surpassed all other beings,
a3 and without effort reached royal dignity. Even now, by the power of virtue I sit upon the diamond throne,
a4 I have [also], without effort, defeated the army of the god Māra [consisting] of 36 times 10 million family members, and the dignity of the king of the world,
a5 the unsurpassable, perfect Buddhahood, ruling all dharmas, I have reached. || In the H.-tune: || through virtue
a6 (beauty) is fine to look at; through virtue the craft of the beings is lovely to look at; through the foundation of virtue, unch(ecked shines)
b1 (wis)dom; through the power of virtue, energy does not weaken. [1.] Through virtue the sun defeats the moon in the airspace;
b2 by merits the moon surpasses the stars and the planets; he who possesses virtue, this one owns the goods of happiness; through virtue
b3 one becomes the venerated Buddha. 2. Therefore the veneration of the Buddha shall ever be carried out by the wise one;
b4 incessantly the energetic ones shall strive to carry out veneration of the Buddha; at the Buddha, the master, the skilled one shall direct veneration;
b5 the handsome one should not tire of homages to the Buddha. 3. In this way wisdom without virtue does not shine, or
b6 rather, only together they are especially bright. Therefore they are themselves called Sambhāras. These two Sambhāras’ (six)</item>
